    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.3-4_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">3</fw>
                
                <fw type="imprint">
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc>Image of la Salle building</figDesc>
                    </figure>
                    La Salle at Madison St.
                        <lb/>
                    Telephone Franklin 0700
                
                    Hotel La Salle
                
                    Chicago January 3 1929</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear John Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Your gracious letter caught me on an extended platform tour. I almost helpless away from home and my typewriter. So...be a good fellow and put up with my scribbling!</p>
                
                <p>No doubt there are passages in my spontaneous letter to you that would be interesting in print. And I should like to say them so &#8212; indeed, I have, couched other-wise. But I had rather not see the letter published as it stands, on two counts. First, I wrote to you hot out of the heart, spontaneously, freely, unguardedly. <hi rend="underline">You</hi> are knit into; <hi rend="underline">I</hi> am; and both of <add>us</add> in a sense <add>are</add> so inextricably knit into my thesis that it would be <unclear>well nigh</unclear> impossible to pull out many impersonal threads. Secondly, I expressed myself in strong language &#8212; and God knows I feel strongly on the subject That is all right in talk and informally. But when one breaks into print he must,
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.3-4_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">4</fw>
                    
                <fw type="imprint">
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc>Image of la Salle building</figDesc>
                    </figure>
                    La Salle at Madison St.
                        <lb/>
                    Telephone Franklin 0700
                    
                    Hotel La Salle
                    
                    Chicago ____________ 192__
                </fw>
                    
                    for the sake of accuracy and persuasiveness <unclear>qualify</unclear> and <unclear>temper</unclear> his comments. Therefore I feel that I'd rather not see the letter <unclear>run</unclear> as a whole.</p>
                
                <p>But if you find passages that you would like to use, and if they are not too acid and likely to stir unnecessary antagonism or too personal,&#8212; go ahead. Feel free to edit whatever passages you may use &#8212; especially if in my haste I failed to express myself as skillfully as I might have. and will you send me a copy of whatever you write on the matter?</p>
                
                <p>Thank you for "Poetic Values", I shall <unclear>look</unclear> for it. And, of course, I should like the new "Straws in the Wind." I feel in advance that I shall like it. It becomes steadily more clear to me that you and I discern much the same literary stars and bow our heads to <add>the</add> same Gods &#8212; <hi rend="underline">and to no others!</hi>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Cordially yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Lew Sarett</signed>
                </closer>
                    
            </div1>
        </body>
        
